lement of sugar and diabetes in the Caribbean, the contributors explore how food and eating create thresholds for human and nonhuman relations. These thresholds mediate different conditions and states of being: between living and dying, between the edible and the inedible, and the relationship between living organisms and their surrounding environment. In this way, acts of eating and the process of metabolism partake in the making and unmaking of multispecies ontologies, taxonomies, and ecologies.Contributors. Alex Blanchette, Deborah Heath, Hannah Landecker, Marianne Elisabeth Lien, Amy Moran-Thomas, Heather Paxson, Harris Solomon, Emily Yates-Doerr, Wim Van Daele  afunded by Duke University  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFood habitsxSocial aspects. 0aFoodxSocial aspects. 0aNutrition policy. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBlanchette, Alex, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDaele, Wim Van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeath, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLandecker, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLien, Marianne Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoran-Thomas, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaxson, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaxson, Heather, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSolomon, Harris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYates-Doerr, Emily, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular